Subject: [PATCH] libstdc++: disable cdtor decloning for MinGW

When libstdc++ is built with -Os, GCC enables constructor/destructor
decloning by default. On MinGW this can make explicit instantiation
objects refer to the old unified constructor/destructor manglings, such
as C4, even though the exported library instantiation only provides the
ABI constructor variants C1 and C2.

For aarch64-w64-mingw32 this shows up while linking libstdc++-6.dll:
the C++20 sources call std::basic_string's move constructor as C4, but
src/c++11/string-inst.o only defines C1 and C2. Build the MinGW
libstdc++ runtime without cdtor decloning so those calls use the public
constructor variants that are actually emitted.

--- a/libstdc++-v3/configure.host
+++ b/libstdc++-v3/configure.host
@@ -292,6 +292,10 @@ case "${host_os}" in
         ;;
     esac
     OPT_LDFLAGS="${OPT_LDFLAGS} \$(lt_host_flags)"
+    # Avoid external references to unified C4/D4 constructor/destructor
+    # symbols from libstdc++ explicit instantiation objects. MinGW exports
+    # the ABI C1/C2 and D1/D2 variants instead.
+    OPTIMIZE_CXXFLAGS="${OPTIMIZE_CXXFLAGS} -fno-declone-ctor-dtor"
     ;;
   netbsd*)
     os_include_dir="os/bsd/netbsd"
